data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you had (e.g., `CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncOverAsync()`) no longer compiles or takes effect.

All four of your synchronous calls will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (required) |
|---|---|
| `.ToList()` | `.ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `.FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `.CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `.SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Fixed code

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory, no I/O.
- Every method that hits Cosmos (queries + `SaveChanges`) must go fully async.
- Callers of these methods will need to be updated to `await` the results, which may ripple up through your controller layer.
